messages.content: 9-1-1, what's your emergency?
Oh my God. I'm on 3rd Avenue by the railroad tracks. Somebody just tried to jump on the train and severed her legs.
Okay. Third Avenue. Can you confirm the cross street?
We're on the west side of the railroad tracks on 3rd Avenue, at Atwood.
Do not move her! An ambulance is on the way. Where's the victim located?
The victim is on the west side. We are at 3rd and Atwood. There were four individuals, one succeeded in jumping, and the other fell.
Okay. I'm going to ask you some questions. Do you have a cell phone?
I have my cell phone, but if I go over there, it's going to be too loud.
That's okay. If you are an EMT, you can probably do more help than anyone else. Let me know when you're with her.
They're on the way. We're not going to put a tourniquet on her. They're like, trying to pick her up.
No, we don't want to move her. Just hold pressure as much as you can.
There's another nurse on scene holding femoral pressure. She's in her early 20s.
Okay. Is she awake and breathing?
She's 17 years old. She is awake and breathing. Her name is Anna.
Is she completely alert?
She's alert and talking. Now she's crying.
Okay. Where is the leg injury located? At the ankle or knee?
One is mid-thigh on the left side. The right leg looks like it's right below the knee.
Is the amputated part still there?
The left leg may not be, but the right leg definitely is.
I've got units on the way. If you can, without traumatizing her, collect those amputated parts if it's safe.
The train's still moving. It's a really long train.
Okay, then don't try to collect them. Do you have something to press against the amputations to control the bleeding?
Yes, we have femoral pressure on the left and a T-shirt around the right.
Good. Just add more if it soaks through and continue with femoral pressure.
We are keeping femoral pressure. Two firefighters are here now.
Okay. I'll let you go so you can talk to them.
Okay, thank you.
You're welcome. Bye.
